ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology of the prepared BiOBr and BNCs (Fig. 1
                        ) was characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM). All materials exhibited the morphology of anisotropic nanosheets with a smooth surface and uniform hierarchical structure, which could enhance light harvesting by generating multiple reflections of light [37]. BiOBr, BNC-ur, and BNC-trp were loosely assembled by stacking nanosheets with a statistical length of about 158.3, 142.1, and 153.9 nm (Fig. 1(a-c)). While BNC-eda was loosely assembled by stacking ultrathin nanosheets with a statistical length of about 117.3 nm (Fig. 1(d)). Therefore, due to the introduction of NC-eda, BNC-eda was smaller and thinner than BiOBr and other BNCs nanosheets, resulting in tighter stacking and morphology more like a graded microflower. This further improved the light-harvesting capability of BNC-eda. Transmission electron microscope (TEM) and high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) results revealed the microstructure of the prepared NCs and BNCs. As shown in Fig. 2
                        (a-c), NCs had great crystallinity and were less than 10 nm in size. Besides, the interplanar spacings of NC-ur, NC-trp, and NC-eda were different, being 0.206 nm, 0.278 nm, and 0.194 nm respectively, corresponding to the (104), (0 0 1 2), and (107) crystal planes of graphite carbon (ICSD. 01–074-2328). HRTEM of BNCs (Fig. S1) showed that the transparent lattice stripes (0.345 nm) coincided with the (101) crystal plane of tetragonal BiOBr, and the lattice stripes with lattice spacings of 0.206 nm, 0.278 nm, and 0.194 nm coincided with the (104), (0 0 1 2), and (107) crystal planes of graphitic carbon, respectively. This demonstrated that the NCs were anchored to the BiOBr surface as expected and the BNCs were successfully synthesized. Furthermore, EDS mapping (Fig. S2) showed uniform distribution of C, N, O, Br, and Bi elements in BNC-eda, further proving the successful introduction of NC-eda.
